## Objective

Prepare a detailed implementation design for Media Library bulk actions.

Bulk actions are higher risk because they affect multiple records, deletion rules, observer behaviour, and media usage protection.

## Scope

Design the workflow for:

- Bulk delete
- Bulk category update
- Bulk visibility update
- Bulk metadata update if practical
- Selection UI
- Confirmation UI
- Partial success reporting
- Safe deletion rules
- Usage protection

## Required Analysis

Review:

- `MediaService`
- `AdminMediaController`
- `MediaObserver`
- `MediaPolicy`
- `Media` model
- `resources/views/admin/cms/media/index.blade.php`
- Existing delete logic
- Existing usage detection logic
- Existing filters and pagination
- Existing grid/list toggle
- Existing category badge logic

## Design Requirements

### Selection UX

Define:

- checkbox placement
- select all on current page
- clear selection
- selected count
- disabled state when nothing is selected
- behaviour across pagination
- behaviour when filters change
- behaviour in grid view
- behaviour in list view

### Bulk Delete

Define:

- confirmation message
- how used media is blocked
- how unused media is deleted
- how partial success is reported
- whether deletion is soft delete or permanent
- whether physical files are removed immediately
- how `MediaObserver` participates
- how `MediaService::delete()` is reused

### Bulk Category Update

Define:

- how selected assets are moved to another category
- whether null/empty category is allowed
- validation rules
- success message
- partial failure handling

### Bulk Visibility Update

Define:

- public/private toggle behaviour
- validation
- affected records
- success message

### Safety Rules

Bulk actions must not:

- bypass existing usage protection
- bypass `MediaService`
- delete files before database checks pass
- delete media used by site settings, pages, insights, case studies, team members, partners, downloads, or any known CMS relation
- introduce N+1 queries
- break existing single-item delete
- break upload
- break replace
- break grid/list view
- break filters
- break pagination

## Performance Requirements

Explain how the implementation will handle:

- 10 selected items
- 50 selected items
- 200 selected items
- partial failures
- database transactions
- chunking if needed

